# Idea and Concept

When I began with this project, I was just starting to learn how programing works. At my school we've just gone over the basics like variables, if-else, for-loops and switch-cases.  
As I was being taught these basic concepts, I started to understand how these could be used to make very simple games. As we've just been writing code that runs in the terminal/console at this point, I figured I'd try to make a little text adventure game that runs completely in the terminal.

I wanted to make something like a "choose your own adventure"-game because those would work well with the programing skills I already had and would lead players down different paths, which I've always found a very cool concept.  
I personally never played the original text-based adventure games like "The Oregon Trail" (1971), "Wanderer" (1974) or "Colossal Cave Adventure" (1976), but I've played some newer web-based games that used the same concepts. I've also seen some books that would also allow one to make choices and then would send you to a different page number depending on what choice you made.

# Implementation

As my programing skills were still quite basic at the time, the code is not very sophisticated. I had not yet learned about functions, so the whole game is written as one singular code block, spanning 6914 lines. This code block includes all of the choices that each of the characters could take, all of the fights, all the endings, everything.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

This project basically lived from switch-case blocks. Each choice the player could take would lead down another switch-case block, so in the end you'd be possibly 8 layers deep which the player thankfully doesn't feel, but the one writing the code does.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

There are also a few boss fights in the game. These are basically just for-loops that end when either the boss or the player has no more hp. These boss fights are round based and basically play somewhat like the fights from the original Pokmon games. There are also some other round based "fights" in the game that don't use skills like in Pokmon games to do damage. There's also a dice game or solving math equations to defeat bosses, but I don't want to spoil everything here.

As I was developing this game, I was also learning some new concepts in school or some new things that one could do with the console. Of course, I have also used those new skills to create some more fun experiences in this game, so the project was basically growing with me while I was learning.

Other than that, there's not a lot more to go over for the development of this game. In the end, it's just some very simple code, a lot of paths, and an absurd amount of manually writing out every single path multiple times.

# Conclusion

The game has a lot of fun ideas in it and a lot of stupid jokes and because of that, quite some charm.

Every time I come back to test out this game, I have again forgotten all the things I put into it, so it's always another personal adventure to find those things again.

I'd recommend this game to anyone that wants to take a few minutes out of their busy and serious day, to go on some fun and wacky adventures.
